1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:08,657
Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto samma-sambuddhassa

2
00:00:09,311 --> 00:00:33,514
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodassa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:35,231 --> 00:00:39,451
So we're carrying on with the candas, these five heaps.

4
00:00:40,494 --> 00:00:42,744
Now, when you look into

5
00:00:43,112 --> 00:01:09,153
the body when you're meditating you can see it's made up first of all of the sensations coming from the body so we did that yes last time the rupa the body and we can break down most of these sensations into these four categories of pressure some sort of weight some sort of

6
00:01:09,134 --> 00:01:17,346
temperature, movement, and some form of cohesiveness, elasticity.

7
00:01:18,626 --> 00:01:27,480
Then there are all these other things that we can feel in the body, feelings that come from the mind that we can describe as emotions.

8
00:01:29,563 --> 00:01:31,986
And thoughts, images.

9
00:01:32,793 --> 00:01:41,283
So that's the Buddha's first three, the rupa, the body, sanya, the perception, and then vedana, feelings.

10
00:01:42,024 --> 00:01:43,805
And tonight we'll do this sanya.

11
00:01:44,647 --> 00:01:55,780
So, in Buddhist psychology, when you attend to something, it will always have a feeling content,

12
00:01:57,058 --> 00:01:59,623
and it will have a perceptive content.

13
00:02:00,284 --> 00:02:01,245
They arise together.

14
00:02:01,265 --> 00:02:03,728
You can't have one without the other.

15
00:02:04,168 --> 00:02:07,513
They're said to be in every moment of attention.

16
00:02:08,474 --> 00:02:15,465
And what the sanya does is it records the basic characteristics of something.

17
00:02:16,586 --> 00:02:25,158
So the zabutons, these mats you're sitting on, the basic thing would be the shape of it, its rectangular shape, and the color.

18
00:02:25,729 --> 00:02:30,400
And it would record that, you see, and these things slowly become your memory.

19
00:02:31,442 --> 00:02:43,046
And by seeing many colors, many shapes, then it begins to discriminate between all the different colors and shapes that you can experience, or that you do experience.

20
00:02:43,786 --> 00:02:46,850
So it's that perceptual memory, you see.

21
00:02:47,752 --> 00:02:53,542
And as it grows to a higher level, then it puts labels on it.

22
00:02:54,002 --> 00:03:00,875
So there's the growth of the intellect coming from the perceptual level, these basic percepts.

23
00:03:03,558 --> 00:03:07,085
And therefore it has the job of recognizing things.

24
00:03:07,104 --> 00:03:08,848
It's your basic memory.

25
00:03:14,413 --> 00:03:29,477
The other factors of a moment of attention you might be interested to know is these two that I've mentioned, the feeling and the perception.

26
00:03:30,298 --> 00:03:40,032
There's also the moment of contact, which I'll come to at another time, which is part of the dependent origination, where you must have an object.

27
00:03:40,789 --> 00:03:45,055
You must have a sense organ and you must have the awareness of it, consciousness.

28
00:03:45,756 --> 00:03:51,663
And remember that there are six sense organs in the Buddha's teaching, the sixth one being the mind itself.

29
00:03:53,566 --> 00:03:56,991
The base of that presumably is the brain, the brain itself.

30
00:03:59,554 --> 00:04:01,417
Then there is will.

31
00:04:01,717 --> 00:04:04,080
There must be some power there.

32
00:04:04,312 --> 00:04:29,882
within that moment just keeping things together and pointing them and then there's that one pointedness of attention it's a quality then there's that quality of attending which is best expressed in that sentence to pay attention it's actually a quality

33
00:04:30,317 --> 00:04:35,084
and it's called mental life faculty.

34
00:04:35,425 --> 00:04:39,290
That's just the basic energy, the basic mental energy.

35
00:04:40,351 --> 00:04:48,884
And it is said that all these seven factors, mental factors are within any given moment of attention.

36
00:04:51,007 --> 00:04:56,915
Now, what happens is that the

37
00:04:57,536 --> 00:05:20,625
quality of these perceptions join with the emotional base and then through the act of will, through that act of attending you get this creativity and at worst it's known as papancha which is a lovely word which means proliferation.

38
00:05:20,824 --> 00:05:22,307
and your mind's going all over the place.

39
00:05:23,028 --> 00:05:36,983
But at its more important level, it's the growth of the conceptual mind, the growth of thinking, and eventually of philosophy and the arts.

40
00:05:37,004 --> 00:05:42,629
So that all begins from that particular perceptual base of sanya.

41
00:05:46,559 --> 00:05:59,331
So we're still really investigating these khanda, the five aggregates into which the Buddha dissected our experience.

42
00:05:59,351 --> 00:06:09,663
So it's the body with its sensations, sanya which were the perceptual faculties which grow into concepts, our intellect.

43
00:06:11,605 --> 00:06:14,608
Today I want to talk about vedana which is feeling.

44
00:06:15,095 --> 00:06:25,718
The fourth was Sankara, which just loosely we can sometimes translate as volitional conditioning, so it's where the will comes in.

45
00:06:26,399 --> 00:06:29,747
And then finally our act of cognition or consciousness.

46
00:06:30,689 --> 00:06:35,178
So just looking at Vedana, so there are

47
00:06:36,322 --> 00:06:41,149
five types and it's a slightly different way of looking at things.

48
00:06:42,713 --> 00:06:43,673
Two of them are physical.

49
00:06:43,733 --> 00:06:45,416
That's pretty straightforward for us.

50
00:06:45,476 --> 00:06:47,860
We have pleasant and unpleasant sensations.

51
00:06:48,360 --> 00:06:50,324
That's pretty easy for us to distinguish.

52
00:06:51,026 --> 00:07:03,124
But there's also distinguished as pleasant and unpleasant mental sensations and that's where the confusion comes in because normally speaking we talk about feelings and emotions.

53
00:07:03,846 --> 00:07:18,345
and I think they shade into each other emotions are very complex things but when you just go into the body they manifest as some sort of feeling

54
00:07:18,528 --> 00:07:46,105
depression is heavy, anger is hot and all that and that's what we're looking at when we are just feeling a sensation in the body which we recognize is caused by a mental state rather than the body itself and it's distinguishing those two and the fifth one is of course the neutral states of both the body sensations and the mental sensations

55
00:07:47,418 --> 00:07:58,173
And the reason we distinguish those two is because the Buddha taught that the physical part of our nature and the mental part were two actually distinct forms of energy.

56
00:07:58,814 --> 00:08:10,471
They both suffered from impermanence, they don't constitute a self or a soul or a person, but they are two different energy systems, the one affecting the other.

57
00:08:10,451 --> 00:08:13,959
And you're sitting when you get a sore knee, the mind becomes agitated.

58
00:08:13,999 --> 00:08:16,684
If you feel depressed, then the mind becomes heavy.

59
00:08:16,764 --> 00:08:20,230
Or if you feel tired, the body becomes heavy.

60
00:08:21,052 --> 00:08:31,531
So that distinguishing, that deconstructing of our experience is part and parcel of understanding

61
00:08:31,512 --> 00:08:49,235
that this psycho-physical organism that we experience ourselves to be does not actually constitute an entity as such, something which is whole, entire, self-subsistent, can exist outside this universe, all that sort of stuff.

62
00:08:49,254 --> 00:08:51,477
It just isn't that.

63
00:08:53,668 --> 00:09:03,542
And you can also, he also splits it up again, dissects it again into the various feelings that arise from the six, well seven senses.

64
00:09:04,423 --> 00:09:15,116
So sight, what we see is also a sensation, it also comes under the physical feelings.

65
00:09:15,417 --> 00:09:20,182
Hearing, what we hear comes under physical feelings, bodily feelings.

66
00:09:20,972 --> 00:09:30,668
So by dividing that, then of course we can see that there are something like 30 different types of sensations and feelings.

67
00:09:33,133 --> 00:09:38,841
These are only types, as you know, within each type there are myriad types of feelings and sensations.

68
00:09:39,943 --> 00:09:48,297
And I dare say, it's never the case that one is exactly the same as the other, like leaves on a tree, they're not the same.

69
00:09:50,993 --> 00:09:58,682
The other thing to say about Vedana is that they're always in any level of consciousness.

70
00:09:59,124 --> 00:10:02,688
So whenever you're conscious, there has to be the factor of Vedana.

71
00:10:02,869 --> 00:10:06,653
So if you're seeing, there's the feeling or sensation of light.

72
00:10:07,274 --> 00:10:10,678
If you're hearing, there's the sensation of sound and so on.

73
00:10:11,159 --> 00:10:19,191
So it's not possible for there to be a conscious moment without there being some sort of feeling.

74
00:10:19,211 --> 00:10:20,932
Now the importance of Vedana

75
00:10:21,605 --> 00:10:32,734
The way he separates this out, feeling, comes up in the discourse on how to establish this right mindfulness, which is about seeking liberation, the Satipaṭṭhāna discourse.

76
00:10:32,953 --> 00:10:38,347
And there's a second section there, after physical feelings, bodily feelings,

77
00:10:38,513 --> 00:11:02,394
there comes vedana-vedanupāsati which means to see feelings in feelings it's a sort of funny construction it's what's known as a locative case where you're in something so it's to feel, to see, to experience feelings in feelings now that seems like a double take

78
00:11:02,375 --> 00:11:18,403
But all he's saying is to try and separate out feelings completely from perceptual things, from emotional fantasies and stuff, and to just center completely on feeling.

79
00:11:18,544 --> 00:11:19,546
What is a feeling?

80
00:11:19,586 --> 00:11:21,769
To ask yourself the question, what is a feeling?

81
00:11:22,432 --> 00:11:24,315
What is a sensation?

82
00:11:24,970 --> 00:11:48,902
because normally speaking we don't experience life in this way we just experience it in the fullness of our personality and physical contact with the world but by doing so it's all part and parcel of seeing how this life works for us and the

83
00:11:49,085 --> 00:12:04,504
This confusion between emotion and feeling, when I say confusion it's the English and it's the way that we experience things, is something that we deal with when we come to the Sankara, which is the next section to do with the will.

84
00:12:04,965 --> 00:12:13,134
So then it becomes quite complicated because everything then begins to motor up into what we would consider an experience.

85
00:12:15,712 --> 00:12:22,807
So that, short and sweet, is the description of Vedana.

86
00:12:23,628 --> 00:12:25,751
I hope my words have been of some assistance.

87
00:12:26,533 --> 00:12:33,267
May you be fully liberated from all your painful Vedana, sooner rather than later.

